<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06172109 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06172109 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  EUROPE; PEACE; ORGANIZATION; BEGIN  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  European and North American nations today created a new system to help mediateconflicts among one another, especially involving the former communistcountries of Eastern Europe.;    Foreign ministers from Europe, Canada and theUnited States also approved the creation of a &quot;hot line&quot; to link membercapitals with the new Conflict Prevention Center in Vienna.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  GLOBAL MEDIATORS SET UPNATIONS CREATE SYSTEM TO DEAL WITH CONFLICTS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The agreement by members of the Conference on Security and Cooperation inEurope, which came at the end of a two-day meeting, calls for nominating amaximum of four experts from each of the 35 members to mediate disputes.;   &quot;At the end of this conference, I can state with great satisfaction we havegone forward a great part of the way to a united European peace order,&quot; saidForeign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher of Germany.;    Genscher, theconference chairman, praised the spirit of cooperation and understanding atthe two-day meeting.;    Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd of Britain said theorganization had moved forward &quot;satisfactorily, without sensation, butusefully.&quot;;    Eastern Europe assurances;  One aim of the conference was togive security assurances to former Soviet-bloc members in Eastern Europe, someof whom have sought membership in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization butwere rebuffed because the alliance did not want to provoke Moscow.;    Despitethe collapse of communism in Eastern Europe two years ago, hot spots ofturmoil, severe economic difficulties and ethnic conflicts remain.;    Theconference agreed on the mechanism for consulting in emergency situations withdeadlines limiting the amount of time before senior officials from the bodymeet to make recommendations for a solution.;    Complaint deadline;  Forinstance, one country's complaint to another country must be answered within48 hours. If the dispute is not resolved, the first country may request anemergency meeting of senior officials, and then there is a deadline of threedays to find 12 countries to second the request.;    The mechanism, however,must not be used to interfere in a country's internal affairs.;    The SovietUnion, diplomats said, insisted on asserting the principle ofnon-interference, fearing the process could be used in its disputes with theBaltic republics.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Berlin  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910620  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  352  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday June 20, 199100172109,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>